title.narrative: MATERNAL & NEWBORN HEALTH

description.narrative: By 2020, primary health care facilities have increased capacity to deliver quality integrated maternal and newborn health services, which contributes to Adolescent Health And Nutrition, Infant And Young Child Feeding, Maternal And Newborn Health, Maternal And Newborn Health (Covid), Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Evaluations, Research And Data, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2020, people, particularly women and young children, more equitably access and use quality health and nutrition services.

title.narrative: By 2020, primary health care facilities have increased capacity to deliver quality integrated maternal and newborn health services

description.narrative: UNICEF approaches such as Every Newborn Action Plan (ENAP), Integrated Management of Children Illnesses (IMCI), neonatal IMCI training of Maternal and Child Health (MHC) nurses – Special Care New-born Units (SNCU) management strengthening and MCH@PCH mentoring modelling have gone a long way at addressing major bottlenecks in Maternal, Newborn, Children and Adolescent Health (MNCAH) quality of care. The MCH and Primary Health Care (PHC) modelling has shown impressive results. SNCU shall be a focus for 2020. Refresher training on Infant, Young and Child Feeding (IYCF) practices reached 93 health workers, contributing to the improvement of infant feeding practices | Status:On-track | As-of Date:01/01/2020
